    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-12-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="339" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d339">
                <head>No. 339.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Foster</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-12-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">December</hi> 29, 1883</date>.
                            (Received January 19, 1884.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 132.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: As supplementary to my No. 121, of the 15th
                        instant, in regard to slavery in Cuba, I desire to add, as an indication of
                        the progress being made towards complete emancipation, that it appears from
                        the official report just published that on the 6th ultimo there were in Cuba
                        99,566 “<hi rend="italic">patrocinados”</hi> (the legal term applied to
                        those still held in bondage). In the year 1868, before the Moret
                        emancipation law was enacted, there were registered 385,356 slaves.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JOHN W. FOSTER.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
